00:41.720 --> 00:49.080
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Michael Whelan. He has to be recognized as
the hottest artist going in the science fiction and fantasy field. In the fall

00:49.080 --> 00:56.340
of 1983, he won the latest of several Hugos he's garnered as the best artist
doing science fiction and fantasy work. We spoke with Whelan recently and asked

00:56.340 --> 01:07.660
him when his interest in science fiction and fantasy art began. I think it
developed when I was born. My father's always worked in the space industry or in

01:07.660 --> 01:17.460
the missiles and space industry. So I had that input around me. He had always
been reading science fiction since I was young. So I had the magazines around to

01:17.460 --> 01:27.960
look at. Some of my earliest recollections are of looking at the covers of old
amazing stories, magazines, or paperback books. In fact, some of them influenced

01:27.960 --> 01:37.400
me to a great deal. Before I could even read or write, I remember looking at
some of those covers for hours and absorbing the visual feeling of the

01:37.400 --> 01:48.060
paintings. There were a few that were especially captivating for me. And I
remember them to this day, exactly what the paintings look like. And I could

01:48.060 --> 01:55.740
describe to you the compositions and some of the colors of the paintings. And
it's a funny thing. At the last World Science Fiction Convention, I was walking

01:55.740 --> 02:04.660
down by one of the dealer's tables in the dealer's room. And I just started
going through some of the paperback books. And I saw one of the covers that I

02:04.660 --> 02:14.020
remembered from when I was three years old or whatever. It was interesting to me
because I hadn't been able, in retrospect, to pinpoint the exact time when I

02:14.020 --> 02:23.080
started really being fascinated by science fiction imagery. And this book had
been published in 1952 or 1953. So being born in 1950, that pretty much

02:23.080 --> 02:35.140
establishes the beginning of that at around three years old or so. But the fact
that it meant so much to me that I remembered that exact cover until my present

02:35.140 --> 02:46.340
age says something about how I guess it was just a part of me that that kind of
imagery was important to me. But later when I began to read, I became an avid

02:46.340 --> 02:55.540
reader of all types of literature, but especially science fiction and fantasy.
And I had an interest in art, so the two combined. And it seemed natural to me

02:55.540 --> 03:04.220
to read and try to draw what I read. And I would come home sometimes from
science fiction movies or movies that I enjoyed and try to illustrate scenes

03:04.220 --> 03:10.180
that I'd seen in the movie from memory. And that carried on pretty much right
into my college years.

03:20.980 --> 03:33.780
In college, Whelan had no plans on becoming an artist. He was, in fact, a pre
-med student. In college, I had been laboring under the assumption that I had to

03:33.780 --> 03:42.860
have a real type of profession. This is largely due to input from my parents,
but I felt that I had to. To be something professional like a lawyer, something

03:42.860 --> 03:45.760
respectable, which being an artist isn't.

03:48.440 --> 03:56.980
So I was diverted during my college years into wanting to become a doctor, which
is still a major interest of mine. Anatomy and physiology and the sciences in

03:56.980 --> 04:07.200
general were always important to me. But about three quarters of the way through
my college education, I decided to abandon my pre-med training and go full

04:07.200 --> 04:15.240
scale. Well, actually, it wasn't until my last year of college that I decided
full tilt to go into illustrating or painting. And I graduated with a degree in

04:15.240 --> 04:24.060
painting. If I had taken one more course, I would have had a degree in biology
with an emphasis on anatomy and physiology, human anatomy and physiology. Whelan

04:24.060 --> 04:33.740
pays special attention to the human form in his art. There's a reason for that.
One of the jobs I had when I was putting myself through college was working in

04:33.740 --> 04:41.320
the anatomy and physiology labs at the university I went to preparing the
cadavers for the classes. And during that time, I managed to get some work in

04:41.320 --> 04:50.860
doing medical illustrations. All this combined to really give me a good
fundamental education in the way the body is made up. More next time with

04:50.860 --> 04:51.520
Michael Whelan.

