06:21.520 --> 06:23.160
And here are your hosts.

06:27.260 --> 06:33.980
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Hugo Award-winning artist Michael Whelan
has always been a reader of science fiction and fantasy. His love of the field

06:33.980 --> 06:41.240
inspires his work. Among other things, Whelan paints covers for science fiction
and fantasy books. He's the most successful artist in his field right now, and

06:41.240 --> 06:47.540
if you read any science fiction at all, you've seen and admired one of his
covers. How does Whelan come up with an idea for a book cover? Say for his well

06:47.540 --> 06:56.620
-known painting on Anne McCaffrey's The White Dragon. That's going back away. That's
back in 77 or 78 when I did that. Let me think. Well, I read the book one time,

06:56.800 --> 07:11.320
just read it as a reader, so to speak. Then I go through it again the second
time as an illustrator, making notes and margins about details of the way people

07:11.320 --> 07:21.400
and objects and things look, making sure that I try to catch all the details so
I don't make someone who's blonde, black-haired or whatever, you know, because I

07:21.400 --> 07:30.500
like to be really true to the story as much as possible, especially if I'm
taking a narrative approach to doing an illustration. After going through it

07:30.500 --> 07:40.780
that second time, I'll sit down and start to develop thumbnail sketches, which
are just small drawings on scrap paper, actually, and try to find an idea of

07:40.780 --> 07:49.760
what I would like to illustrate from that book. There's usually something in any
book, no matter how bad or good, that will make a good painting. It's a matter

07:49.760 --> 08:00.320
of digging through it and finding what it leads to you and what will motivate
you to do a really good job. So I go through it and try to collate all my

08:00.320 --> 08:08.280
different ideas and put it together into a painting. That is the mysterious part
that I can't really describe to you, how that happens. I guess that's what makes

08:08.280 --> 08:19.140
me what I am, is that process there of distilling what I've read into something
that's a visual image that captures what's in the book. But that process takes a

08:19.140 --> 08:31.760
few days to do, and sometimes I get an instant image. The cover I just did for
Robert A. Heinlein's book, Friday, I had an instantaneous concept of what that

08:31.760 --> 08:40.120
cover was going to look like. As soon as I finished reading the book the first
time, I had, I think, a perfectly clear idea of what Friday looked like. And I

08:40.120 --> 08:50.500
knew that the cover to this book had to be a portrait of this character, because
the character had such, well, she had such personality that the book was written

08:50.500 --> 08:51.780
around her personality, I think.

09:02.660 --> 09:11.800
And if he ever gets any feedback from authors whose book covers he's done. Yes,
lots of times. In fact, with Friday, I got a phone call from Robert A. Heinlein

09:11.800 --> 09:22.180
about a couple months after I turned in the painting to Ballantine Del Rey. They
sent him a cover proof, which is a first-run color tryout of what the cover's

09:22.180 --> 09:30.780
going to look like. And he called me up to tell me it was the, it was a little
flattery, I guess. He told me it was the best cover he ever had on a book of

09:30.780 --> 09:38.860
his, which is really quite a statement for someone who's been in the field as
long as he has. And to have an author tell me that I've captured a particular

09:38.860 --> 09:48.440
character or scene exactly the way they had it in mind is probably, for me, the
highest praise that an illustrator can get. And that really had me floating up

09:48.440 --> 09:56.200
by the ceiling for a couple weeks to think that he would bother to call me to
tell me that. But sometimes before I do a painting, I'll correspond with an

09:56.200 --> 10:06.840
author or talk to him or her on the phone to establish certain details. With the
white dragon, for example, I talked to Anne McCaffrey at length about the actual

10:06.840 --> 10:15.900
details of the dragons as she saw the dragons in her book, whether they had
forked tails or tails that ended in a point or whatever, or a barb or whatever,

10:16.120 --> 10:24.780
and what their skin was like and what the texture was so that I could try to
capture her image of what they look like. It's kind of silly for someone who's

10:24.780 --> 10:31.600
an illustrator to try to make all that up when you can contact the author and
get the details, if they're not in the book, straight from the person who

10:31.600 --> 10:35.720
thought them up. We'll continue our conversation with Michael Whelan on our next
show.

