12:13.520 --> 12:20.040
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Multiple award-winning science fiction
artist Michael Whelan has done the cover art on many of the blockbusters in the

12:20.040 --> 12:26.840
science fiction and fantasy field recently. The cover painting for Anne
McCaffrey's The White Dragon was probably his first well-known cover. Since then

12:26.840 --> 12:34.820
he's done the art for Arthur Clarke's 2010: Odyssey Two, Robert Heinlein's Friday,
and Isaac Asimov's Foundation's Edge. We asked Whelan if he has a favorite type

12:34.820 --> 12:44.680
of subject for his paintings. I think one thing that you can say about my work
is that I try to cover all the fields. And that's because it's all, I don't have

12:44.680 --> 12:54.120
any particular favorite. I think I could say I have a favorite assignment each
year. There's one assignment I get every year that's the one I look forward to.

12:54.340 --> 13:01.400
It's a regular thing now with DAW books, and that's the year's best horror
stories cover. It's a collection of horror stories, supposedly the year's best.

13:03.660 --> 13:08.640
And I have completely free reign, like I often do with book covers, but
especially with this one.

13:11.620 --> 13:18.660
And that's enjoyable to me. I like doing a good horror painting once in a while.
I'm not a person who's interested at all in blood and guts. That's not

13:18.660 --> 13:28.520
necessarily what I, I equate that more with revulsion than I do with horror.
There's a difference. But that is a lot of fun, and I've enjoyed doing that

13:28.520 --> 13:37.760
cover every year, that painting, I should say. I've come up with a few pretty
scary ideas that they've never let me paint, too. Someday that I'll do just for

13:37.760 --> 13:46.260
myself. But, you know, that's only one aspect. I like, of course, the other
aspects of science fiction and fantasy. Also, I like to paint. I like the

13:46.260 --> 13:53.780
exploration of space, what they call hardware paintings with spaceships and all
that. That's a lot of fun. I like to just kind of keep my fingers in all of it.

13:53.860 --> 14:01.820
So I can't really say I have a, especially having a favorite, you know, field.
Horror is one of them, and that particular job is probably my favorite

14:01.820 --> 14:12.620
assignment out of the year. But I can't say it's doing horror is something I
like to do over doing other things. We've all seen the gaudy and attention

14:12.620 --> 14:19.060
-getting covers in science fiction and fantasy books. Maybe you've even been
influenced to buy a book because of its cover. We asked Whelan if a cover can

14:19.060 --> 14:30.120
sell a science fiction book. I honestly don't know. I really don't know.
Sometimes I think it makes a big difference. Other times I don't. You know, the

14:30.120 --> 14:36.500
fact that my career has gone where it has and that sometimes

14:36.500 --> 14:45.660
I think it makes a big difference. The fact that I'm getting paid what I do and
everything to do these covers and that the publishers seem to think that my work

14:45.660 --> 14:49.600
sells books over

14:49.600 --> 14:57.140
just the title and the name of the author makes me think sometimes that the
artwork has a lot to do with that. There are other times when you'll see a

14:57.140 --> 15:06.220
bestseller that has an absolutely wretched cover or has nothing but type on it
that's selling quite well. Then you think the cover art has absolutely nothing

15:06.220 --> 15:15.840
to do with it. So it's really hard to say. It's a balance, I think, between how
famous the author is, how much publicity the book has gotten, and the

15:15.840 --> 15:19.080
expectations

15:19.080 --> 15:30.240
that people have had before the book's been published. A book like Foundation's
Edge, the Foundation series by Isaac Asimov has a large readership. They've been

15:30.240 --> 15:38.380
waiting for this book and it's come out. So, you know, they could have put a
black cover with just the title Foundation's Edge on it and that thing would

15:38.380 --> 15:45.160
have sold, you know, off the shelf. But just to be sure, they've hired me to do
the paperback cover for that book. But, you know,

15:48.580 --> 16:01.080
books that have large, very large, that are published in large publications have
large budgets. And so they can afford to have a good cover for that. And I think

16:01.080 --> 16:10.880
that's why it's true as, let's see, what's his name? The founder of Dell. His
last name is Dell Accord. I don't remember his first name. Anyway, he said, what

16:10.880 --> 16:21.320
you do is, when you have a good painter, good cover artist, is use them for your
best books or your worst books. As the top cover artist working today, Whelan

16:21.320 --> 16:22.380
gets a lot of both types.

