18:02.740 --> 18:09.580
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Richard Curtis is a New York literary
agent who represents a number of today's most popular science fiction authors.

18:09.860 --> 18:17.160
He also writes a column for Locus Magazine, the best-known publication in the
science fiction and fantasy field. The column is called Agent's Corner, and it's

18:17.160 --> 18:26.640
full of advice for any kind of author, not just science fiction and fantasy
writers. We asked Curtis about the origin of his column. Well, about two and a

18:26.640 --> 18:42.700
half years ago, I was invited to address a group of authors, the American
Society of Journalists and Authors. And I chose to talk to them about certain

18:42.700 --> 18:55.740
contractual clauses that I thought might be pitfalls for most professional
authors. In the questioning that followed, I found an appalling ignorance on the

18:55.740 --> 19:09.500
part of authors on the subject of contracts. And many of these people are highly
respected professional journalists and book authors. And yet it was clear to me

19:09.500 --> 19:21.160
that they didn't know anything, or very much, I should say, about how to read a
contract, how to negotiate one, and how to alter a clause to their own benefit.

19:21.160 --> 19:32.940
And so I decided to write a column for the many other writers who were probably
on the same position. And I asked Charles Brown, the editor of Locus, the

19:32.940 --> 19:46.980
publisher of Locus, I guess, whether he'd be interested in publishing it. And he
was quite agreeable. And thereafter, a number of magazines, newsletters

19:46.980 --> 19:59.800
published by other writers groups, such as Western Writers of America, Romance
Writers of America, Mystery Writers of America, took on the column because they

19:59.800 --> 20:08.340
felt their authors were in the same position. We asked Curtis if he would mind
telling us some of the science fiction authors he represents. Well, no, I don't

20:08.340 --> 20:22.360
mind at all. It's, I think, a fairly common knowledge in the science fiction
community. We represent Harlan Ellison, Gregory Benford, Greg Bear, Elizabeth

20:22.360 --> 20:37.680
Lynn, Marta Randall, Barry Longyear, Warren Norwood, Jessica Salmonson, and I'd
say three or four more.

20:44.260 --> 20:51.360
Since Curtis represents all sorts of authors who write for the paperbacks, we
asked him about the popularity of genre literature, such as Westerns, romances,

20:51.540 --> 20:57.840
mysteries, science fiction, and so forth. The publishers, for instance, create
the market for these books and thereby, in a sense, determine readers' taste.

20:57.840 --> 21:13.400
It's hard to say. Sometimes the publishers create the taste, and sometimes the
market, the consumer, creates the demand. Sometimes it's the agent. For

21:13.400 --> 21:25.840
instance, I find myself very often in speaking to publishers, I find myself in a
double role. I keep my ears open and try to listen to what a publisher tells me

21:25.840 --> 21:37.720
about what he's able to sell and what he's not able to sell. And so I have a
kind of passive role in that I pass along to authors what the publishers tell me

21:37.720 --> 21:51.640
the market is doing. However, if I begin to notice a trend, I then try to help
create a market by turning to other publishers and saying, listen, I've had

21:51.640 --> 22:03.980
lunch the last couple of months with four publishers, and they all tell me that
hard science fiction is not as active as fantasy and sword and sorcery, and so

22:03.980 --> 22:15.400
maybe you'd be interested in some sort of sorcery. So an agent is in the
position of shaping the market once he begins to detect the trend. More next

22:15.400 --> 22:16.560
time with Agent Richard Curtis.

