23:54.300 --> 24:01.740
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Richard Curtis has been a literary agent
for over 25 years, and he represents some of today's most popular science

24:01.740 --> 24:08.860
fiction and fantasy authors. He also writes a column in the science fiction
magazine Locus, which contains all sorts of practical advice for writers of any

24:08.860 --> 24:15.780
genre. Many science fiction fans, of course, have often wondered if they could
make it as writers. We asked Curtis if he had any advice for aspiring science

24:15.780 --> 24:29.360
fiction or fantasy authors. Always begin with the magazines. You're absolutely
right about science fiction fans being more fanatic, but they are also fortunate

24:29.360 --> 24:43.640
in having a place where they can begin in the shorter media, where most writers
in other genres don't have the chance. I mean, there are very few places where a

24:43.640 --> 24:56.820
romance writer can teethe. You know, you can't write romance short stories
unless you try to write for some of the slicker women's magazines, and they're,

24:56.880 --> 25:11.140
of course, very demanding in what they accept. There used to be Western
magazines, many, many of them, but those, almost all of them, are gone now.

25:12.100 --> 25:25.320
Mystery magazines, there are still a couple of them, but it's not like what it
used to be when I got into the business about 25 years ago. So one of the few

25:25.320 --> 25:38.420
remaining genres that invites new talent and cultivates it is science fiction,
where you have very active magazine market and anthology market for original

25:38.420 --> 25:47.900
stories. Besides this advice, Curtis says there's one particular aspect of
science fiction that can also help a beginning writer. You also have

25:47.900 --> 25:59.100
conventions. Of course, Western writers, romance writers, mystery writers also
have their conventions, but certainly science fiction writers can out-convention

25:59.100 --> 26:13.600
anybody by a ratio of 10 to 1. So there's a lot of interplay where authors are
always talking to one another, meeting editors, meeting professional writers,

26:13.920 --> 26:28.440
and there's a much tighter unity than there is in any other genre. So I would
definitely advise any aspiring science fiction writer to start writing in the

26:28.440 --> 26:43.940
magazines. In fact, even some of my well-known clients, I still tell them to
continue writing for science fiction magazines, even though they may get peanuts

26:43.940 --> 26:57.040
for their work compared to what they can get writing books, because the exposure
among both science fiction editors and science fiction fans is terribly

26:57.040 --> 27:05.140
important. Regular readers of science fiction and fantasy have certainly noticed
a great number of trilogies in the past few years. Right. It almost seems as if

27:05.140 --> 27:12.800
authors plan on writing a three-book series when they begin a novel. We asked
Curtis if he, as an agent, liked to receive trilogies from his authors. The

27:12.800 --> 27:26.200
beauty of a trilogy, of course, is, from an agent's viewpoint, is in the kind of
package deal that one can make, where you not only sign an author up for a book,

27:26.280 --> 27:38.620
but you can sign him up for a sequel and a sequel after that. And the author
knows where he's going to be two years from now. The publisher knows what he can

27:38.620 --> 27:51.420
expect over a couple of years. And unless the author one day runs out of steam
or gets bored with the characters that he developed in book one or two, you can

27:51.420 --> 28:03.780
see a cumulative effect in the sales of a trilogy, where publication of book two
makes people scurry for book one, and publication of book three causes the

28:03.780 --> 28:16.260
publisher to reissue books one and two, and then they put them in a box set, and
they're reviewed as a whole. It's a very nice way of publishing books, but not

28:16.260 --> 28:18.020
everybody has a sequel in them.

